\b 3.3.3 Model Architecture\par
\b0\par
This section discusses the three model variants used in the project. The discussion is organised into: (1) the baseline encoder-decoder CNN, (2) the CNN with an additional convolutional bottleneck layer, and (3) the hybrid CNN model with a MobileViT-style bottleneck, skip connections, and residual output. For each model, the architectural design, training behaviour, validation behaviour, and metric trends are interpreted using the generated plots.\par
\par
\b 3.3.3.1 Baseline Model\par
\b0\par
The baseline model is a lightweight encoder-decoder CNN that uses only convolution, ReLU activation, max pooling, bilinear upsampling, and a sigmoid output layer. In this structure, the encoder gradually extracts features from the degraded underwater image, while the decoder reconstructs an enhanced image from the compressed representation. The baseline model does not include an explicit bottleneck module or skip connections. Its purpose is to provide a simple reference architecture so that more advanced variants can be compared against it.\par
\par
In this model, the image first passes through the encoder, where the feature depth increases from 3 channels to 32 channels and then to 64 channels. Spatial resolution is reduced through max pooling so that the model can learn compressed representations. The decoder then upsamples the compressed feature map step by step and maps it back to a 3-channel enhanced image. Since the design is simple, the model is computationally efficient and easy to optimise, but it has limited capacity for capturing complex contextual relationships across the full image.\par
\par
