\par
\b Training and Validation Loss Behaviour\par
\b0\par
The training loss curve and the validation loss curve show that the baseline model learns meaningful enhancement mappings throughout training. At the beginning, the training loss is relatively high at approximately 0.0853 and the validation loss is around 0.0628. As the epochs progress, both curves show a consistent downward trend. By epoch 100, the training loss decreases to about 0.0390, while the validation loss decreases to about 0.0396.\par
\par
This trend suggests that the model is converging and learning stable feature mappings rather than behaving randomly. The decreasing validation loss confirms that the learned representation generalises to unseen paired validation samples. The gap between training loss and validation loss remains small across training, which suggests that severe overfitting is not present. Small oscillations are visible in some epochs, but these are normal in deep learning optimisation and do not indicate divergence. Overall, the baseline model is trainable, stable, and able to learn the enhancement task, although its final performance remains limited compared with more advanced architectures.\par
\par
