\par
\b Inference from the Loss Curves\par
\b0\par
The loss curves indicate that the baseline architecture is capable of learning the task without instability. The smooth reduction in both curves implies successful optimisation. Since the validation curve follows the training curve closely, the model is not strongly underfitting or overfitting by the end of training. However, because the architecture is simple and lacks richer feature refinement mechanisms, its representational strength is lower than the later models.\par
\par
\b PSNR and SSIM Behaviour\par
\b0\par
The PSNR curve rises from approximately 21.79 in the first epoch to 26.15 by epoch 100. This indicates that the reconstructed output becomes increasingly closer to the paired target images over time. The SSIM curve also rises substantially, from around 0.5792 to 0.8520, showing that the structural similarity between the predicted output and the target image improves steadily.\par
\par
These trends confirm that the baseline model is not only reducing training loss but is also improving objective image-quality similarity with the target references. The PSNR increase shows better pixel-level fidelity, while the SSIM increase shows better preservation of structural image content. The gradual saturation of both curves near later epochs suggests that the model approaches a stable performance limit.\par
\par
