\par
\b Inference from the PSNR and SSIM Curves\par
\b0\par
The baseline model clearly learns useful enhancement behaviour. Both curves show consistent upward movement and do not collapse during training. This means the architecture is valid and trainable. However, the later comparison results show that this model is not the strongest performer among the three. It provides a stable baseline rather than the highest final enhancement quality.\par
\par
\b 3.3.3.2 CNN + Bottleneck Layer\par
\b0\par
The second model extends the baseline encoder-decoder design by adding a dedicated convolutional bottleneck block between the encoder and decoder. This bottleneck consists of two convolutional layers operating at the compressed feature level. The purpose of this addition is to provide deeper feature transformation before reconstruction, allowing the network to learn more complex restoration patterns than the baseline architecture.\par
\par
The encoder again extracts hierarchical features from the 3-channel input image and compresses the representation to 64 channels at a smaller spatial scale. Instead of passing directly to the decoder, the encoded representation is processed through the bottleneck, where deeper convolutional refinement is performed. The decoder then reconstructs the enhanced image using bilinear upsampling and convolution. This design increases representational power while remaining simpler than a hybrid transformer-based model.\par
\par
\b [Insert Model 2 Block Diagram Here]\par
