\par
\b Inference from the Loss Curves\par
\b0\par
The lower final loss values compared with the baseline indicate that the bottleneck adds useful representational depth. The model learns more effectively and maintains stable validation behaviour. This means the bottleneck is helping the network capture richer restoration patterns rather than simply increasing complexity without benefit.\par
\par
\b PSNR and SSIM Behaviour\par
\b0\par
For Model 2, PSNR increases from about 20.89 at the beginning of training to approximately 26.45 by epoch 100. SSIM rises from around 0.5405 to about 0.8575. These curves show that the model gains both pixel-level reconstruction quality and structural similarity during training. Compared with the baseline model, Model 2 finishes with a higher PSNR and a slightly higher SSIM, which indicates that the bottleneck improves fidelity to the ground-truth target images.\par
\par
The PSNR curve exhibits a generally increasing trend with some small local fluctuations, while SSIM also improves steadily. These fluctuations are expected because metric-based evaluation can vary across epochs even when overall learning is improving. The key point is that both curves end higher than those of the baseline, showing a real benefit from the bottleneck design.\par
\par
